ch]], [[Gert Boyle]], [[James DePreist]], [[Sho Dozono]], [[Jack Faust (attorney)|Jack Faust]], [[Peggy Fowler]], [[Neil Goldschmidt]], [[Mark Hatfield]], [[Barron Hilton]], [[Vera Katz]], [[John Kitzhaber]], [[Phil Knight]], [[Robert B. Pamplin]], [[Fred Stickel]], and [[Charles Swindells]].
==Description== The [[watercolor painting]] measures {{Convert|8.5|ft|m}} by {{Convert|4.5|ft|m}} and depicts 54 prominent residents of the city during the 1990s,<ref name="Perry">{{cite news|last1=Perry|first1=Douglas|title=Iconic mural showcasing 1990s Portland luminaries is back: How many faces do you recognize?|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/history/2018/03/iconic_hotel_mural_showcasing.html|accessdate=March 15, 2018|work=[[The Oregonian]]|date=March 14, 2018|publisher=[[Advance Publications]]|issn=8750-1317}}</ref> and who "have played roles in modern Portland".<ref name="Famous">{{cite news|last1=Killen|first1=John|title=Painting of downtown Portland with famous residents donated to Oregon Historical Society|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/history/2015/01/painting_of_downtown_portland.html|accessdate=March 15, 2018|work=The Oregonian|date=January 12, 2015}}</ref> ''[[The Oregonian]]''{{'s}} Douglas Perry described the mural as "Portland's own version of the ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'' LP cover".<ref name=Perry/> People painted in the mural include:<ref name="Perry" />
{{Div col|colwidth=15em}} * Shirley Berselli * Mary Bishop * Owen Blank * [[Stephen Bollenbach]] * Gwyneth Booth * [[Gert Boyle]] * [[James DePreist]] * [[Sho Dozono]] * Serge D'Rovencourt * John Eskildsen * [[Jack Faust (attorney)|Jack Faust]] * [[Peggy Fowler]] * Gerry Frank * Stan Geffen * [[Neil Goldschmidt]] * Joseph Ha * Antoinette Hatfield * [[Mark Hatfield]] * [[Barron Hilton]] * Dieter Huckestein * Jerry Hulsman * Brad Hutton * Roy Jay * [[Vera Katz]] * Ruth Keller * [[John Kitzhaber]] * Sharon LaCroix Kitzhaber * [[Phil Knight]] * Peter Kohler * Bud Lindstrand * Hillman Lueddemann Jr. * Melvin "Pete" Mark Jr. * Michael Maslowsky * Carol McCall * Diane McCall * Larry Ogg * [[Robert B. Pamplin]] * Ron Ragen * Dick Reiten * Bob Ridgley * Paul Romain * Hilmar Rosenast * Jim Rudd * Arlene Schnitzer * Ethel Simon-McWilliams * Del Smith * [[Fred Stickel]] * Peter Stott * [[Charles Swindells]] * Ron Timpe * Ben Whiteley * Nancy Wilgenbusch * Ted Winnowski * Dick Woolworth {{Div col end}}
The Portlanders are gathered near the intersection of Southwest [[Broadway (Portland, Oregon)|Broadway]] and Morrison Street, and several of the city's buildings are shown in the background,<ref name="Killen">{{cite news|last1=Killen|first1=John|title=Portland painting: Who are those people in artwork donated to Oregon Historical Society? Check the key|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/history/2015/01/portland_painting_who_are_thos.html|accessdate=March 15, 2018|work=The Oregonian|date=January 15, 2015}}</ref> including the [[Broadway Building (Portland, Oregon)|Broadway Building]], [[Hilton Portland Hotel]], [[Jackson Tower]], Nordstrom, [[Pioneer Courthouse]], and the [[Standard Insurance Center]].<ref name=Famous/>
==History== The mural was commissioned by Serge D'Rovencourt, a former manager of the Hilton Portland Hotel, and originally displayed in the hotel's restaurant, called Bistro 921, starting in 1995.<ref name=Perry/> In 2014, the hotel and bistro were remodeled and the painting was donated to the [[Oregon Historical Society]].<ref name=Killen/> The work was displayed in the [[Oregon Historical Society Museum]]'s North Wing Gallery in early 2015,<ref name=Famous/><ref name="PT">{{cite news|title=Hilton's prominent people portrait on its way to historical society museum|url=http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/246919-115056-hiltons-prominent-people-portrait-on-its-way-to-historical-society-museum|accessdate=March 15, 2018|work=[[Portland Tribune]]|publisher=[[Pamplin Media Group]]|date=January 14, 2015|oclc=46708462}}</ref> for was showcased again for one month in 2018.<ref name="Perry" />
==Reception== ''The Oregonian''{{'s}} John Killen called the painting "fun" and "fanciful",<ref name=Killen/> and Douglas Perry said the mural was a "local favorite".<ref name="Perry" />
