{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}} {{Use British English|date=October 2013}} {{Infobox theatre group | name = Forced Entertainment | image = | imagesize = | caption = | formed = 1984 | disbanded = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | genre = | location = Sheffield | members = | ArtisticDirector = [[Tim Etchells]] | notable = | homepage = {{URL|www.forcedentertainment.com}} }}
'''Forced Entertainment''' is an [[experimental theatre]] company based in [[Sheffield]], England, founded by [[Tim Etchells]] in 1984.<ref name="bbc-radio-4">{{cite web|url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01k12qv | date = 18 June 2012 | accessdate = 18 November 2013 | publisher = [[BBC]] | title = Forced Entertainment}}</ref><ref name="aesthetica">{{cite web|url = http://www.aestheticamagazine.com/experimental-theatre-provoking-ideas | accessdate = 27 October 2013 | last = Fairweather | first = Shona Fairweather | publisher = [[Aesthetica magazine]] | title = Experimental Theatre: Provoking Ideas}}</ref><ref name="robert-avila">{{cite news |url = http://www.sfbg.com/2012/12/04/london-diary | date = 4 December 2012 | accessdate = 18 November 2013 | first= Robert |last= Avila | publisher = [[San Francisco Bay Guardian]] | title = London diary}}</ref><ref name="mary-brennan">{{cite news |url = http://www.heraldscotland.com/arts-ents/stage/forced-entertainment-storm-back-with-two-shows.22362114 | date = 7 October 2013 | accessdate = 18 November 2013 | first= Mary |last= Brennan | publisher = [[Sunday Herald]] | title = Forced Entertainment Storm back with two shows}}</ref>
==Details and history== Forced Entertainment originally focused on making and touring theatre performances before expanding to long durational performance, live art, video and digital media.<ref name="mary-brennan" /><ref name="lyn-gardner-guardian-crazy" /> Their work has been presented throughout the UK and Europe<ref name="mary-brennan" /> as well as Australia, Japan, Canada and the US.<ref name="aesthetica" /><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.britishcouncil.org/arts-performanceinprofile-2010-forced-entertainment.htm | accessdate = 27 October 2013 | title = Forced Entertainment - Performance in Profile 2010| publisher = British Council=|publisher british council=}}</ref> They develop projects using a collaborative process – devising work as a group through improvisation, experimentation and debate.<ref name="aesthetica" /><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/funding/browse-regularly-funded-organisations/npo/forced-entertainment-ltd/ | accessdate = 27 October 2013 | publisher = Arts Council England | title = Forced Entertainment Ltd}}</ref> Their core members are [[Tim Etchells]] (artistic director),<ref name="bbc-radio-4" /><ref name="aesthetica" /> Richard Lowdon (designer and performer)<ref name="aesthetica" /> and performers Robin Arthur,<ref name="aesthetica" /><ref name="joyce-mcmillan">{{cite news |url = http://www.scotsman.com/what-s-on/theatre-comedy-dance/theatre-review-tomorrow-s-parties-glasgow-1-3138994 | date = 12 October 2013 | accessdate = 18 November 2013 | first= Joyce |last= McMillan | publisher = [[The Scotsman]] | title = Theatre review: Tomorrow's Parties, Glasgow}}</ref> Claire Marshall,<ref name="aesthetica" /><ref name="joyce-mcmillan" /> Cathy Naden<ref name="aesthetica" /> and Terry O'Connor,<ref name="aesthetica" /> who have all been with the company from the start.<ref name="bbc-radio-4" /><ref name="lyn-gardner-guardian-war">{{cite news |url = https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2009/feb/23/forced-entertainment-sheffield | date = 23 February 2009 | accessdate = 18 November 2013 | first= Lyn |last= Gardner | publisher = [[The Guardian]] | title = 'We are waging a war'}}</ref>
A book was published about them in 2004, ''"Not Even a Game Anymore": The Theatre of Forced Entertainment''.<ref name="not-even-a-game-anymore-amazon" /> In 2012 [[BBC Radio 4]] aired a programme following their creative process developing, writing and rehearsing ''The Coming Storm''.<ref name="bbc-radio-4" />
==Projects== {{columns-list|colwidth=30em| * ''Jessica in the Room of Lights'', 1984, theatre performances<ref name="keith-peacock">{{cite book |last= Peacock |first= Keith | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=UIgi0UkHKy8C&dq=forced+entertainment+Jessica+in+the+Room+of+Lights | title= Thatcher's Theatre: British Theatre and Drama in the Eighties | accessdate = 20 November 2013 |year= 1999 |publisher= Greenwood Publishing Group | page= 206 | quote = Foremost amongst such groups to emerge during the 1980s was Forced Entertainment which in the context of the urban landscape, confronted contemporary cultural mythology. The company was founded in 1984 and based in Sheffield. Its first "show" was Jessica in the room of Lights (1984). This was followed by Set-up and Nighthawks (1985), Let the Water Run its Course To the Sea That Made the Promise (1986) and The Day that Serenity Returned to the Ground (1986), 200% and Bloody Thirsty (1987) and Some Confusions in the Law About Love (1989) |isbn= 9780313299018}}</ref> * ''The Set-up'', 1985, theatre performances<ref name="keith-peacock" /> * ''Nighthawks'', 1985, theatre performances<ref name="keith-peacock" /> * ''(Let the Water Run its Course) to the Sea that Made the Promise'', 1986, theatre performances<ref name="lyn-gardner-guardian-crazy" /><ref name="keith-peacock" /> * ''The Day that Serenity Returned to the Ground'', 1986, theatre performances<ref name="keith-peacock" /> * ''200% and Bloody Thirsty'', 1987, theatre performances<ref name="keith-peacock" /> * ''Some Confusions in the Law about Love'', 1989, theatre performances<ref name="keith-peacock" /> * ''Marina & Lee'', 1991, theatre performances<ref name="searching-for-redemption">{{cite web|url = http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/10486809408568296 | accessdate = 19 November 2013 | publisher = Taylor & Francis Group | title = Searching for redemption with cardboard wings: Forced entertainment and the sublime}}</ref> * ''Cardboard Sign Photographs'', 1992, photography<ref name="judith-helmer-florian-malzacher-verlag">{{cite book | first1 = Judith | last1 = Helmer | first2 = Florian | last2 = Malzacher | title= "Not Even a Game Anymore": The Theatre of Forced Entertainment |year = 2004 | publisher = Alexander Verlag Berlin | location= Berlin | isbn = 3-89581-115-7 | pages = 293–316}}<!--| accessdate = 26 November 2013 --></ref> * ''Emanuelle Enchanted'', 1992, theatre performances<ref name="searching-for-redemption" /> * ''12 am: Awake & Looking Down'', 1993, long durational performances<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/kulturspiegel/d-8831654.html | date = 24 November 1997 | accessdate = 19 November 2013 | first= Georg |last= Diez | publisher = [[Der Spiegel]] | title = Forced Entertainment}}</ref> * ''Club of No Regrets'', 1993, theatre performances<ref name="dan-venning">{{cite journal | url = https://www.academia.edu/1821789/Performance_Theatre_and_the_Poetics_of_Failure_Forced_Entertainment_Goat_Island_Elevator_Repair_Service_by_Sara_Jane_Bailes_Book_Beview_ | last1 = Venning | first1 = Dan | year=2012 | title = Performance Theatre and the Poetics of Failure: Forced Entertainment, Goat Island, Elevator Repair Service, by Sara Jane Bailes (Book Beview) | periodical = Journal of Dramatic Theatre and Criticism | volume = 26 | issue= 2 | pages=246–8 | publisher = Department of Theatre, University of Kansas | quote = She goes on to suggest that contemporary theatre groups such as Shefeld-based Forced Entertainment (founded 1984), Chicago-based Goat Island (1987-2009), and New York-based Elevator Repair Service (founded 1991) have used and constructed failure as an integral part of their performances. | doi = 10.1353/dtc.2012.0020}}</ref> * ''Looking Forwards'', 1993, photography<ref name="judith-helmer-florian-malzacher-verlag" /> * ''Red Room'', 1993, gallery/installation<ref name="judith-helmer-florian-malzacher-verlag" /> * ''A Decade of Forced Entertainment'', 1994, theatre performances<r