{{nihongo|'''''From the Fatherland, with Love'''''|半島を出よ|Hantō o Deyo}} is a novel by [[Ryū Murakami]], first published in Japanese in 2005 and translated into English in 2013 by Ralph McCarthy, Charles De Wolf, and Ginny Tapley. The novel depicts an [[alternate history]] in which [[North Korea]] invades and then occupies [[Japan]] in 2011.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/dec/22/ryu-murakami-from-fatherland-review|title=From the Fatherland With Love by Ryu Murakami – review|last=Larman|first=Alexander|date=2013-12-22|work=The Guardian|access-date=2016-06-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2013/06/23/books/book-reviews/north-korea-occupies-fukuoka-in-murakamis-alternate-world/|last=Kirzner|first=Eli|title=North Korea occupies Fukuoka in Murakami's alternate world|work=The Japan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2016-06-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://metro.co.uk/2013/05/22/ryu-murakamis-imagined-japanse-history-is-a-phenomenal-feat-of-storytelling-3803175/|title=Ryu Murakami's imagined Japanese history is a phenomenal feat|first=Andrzej|last=Lukowski|date=2013-05-22|website=Metro|access-date=2016-06-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/book-review-from-the-fatherland-with-love-by-ryu-murakami-trans-ralph-mccarthy-charles-de-wolf-and-8755008.html|last=Gibbs|first=Jonathan|title=Book review: From the Fatherland, With Love, By Ryu Murakami, trans.|work=The Independent|date=2013-08-09|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-06-26}}</ref>

== Awards ==
''From the Fatherland With Love'' was awarded the 59th {{Interlanguage link multi|Mainichi Publishing Culture Award|ja|3=毎日出版文化賞}} and the 58th [[Noma Literary Prize]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jlpp.go.jp/jp/works/05_13.html|script-title=ja:『半島を出よ』第5回選定作品|trans-title=''From the Fatherland With Love'': 5th Selected Work|publisher=Japanese Literature Publishing Project, [[Agency for Cultural Affairs (Japan)|Agency for Cultural Affairs]]|access-date=28 June 2016}}</ref>

