{{Infobox artwork | title = The Great God Pan | image_size = | alt = | caption = The sculpture in 2014 | painting_alignment = | other_language_1 = | other_title_1 = | other_language_2 = | other_title_2 = | artist = [[George Grey Barnard]] | year = {{start date|1898}} | catalogue = | type = Sculpture | subject = [[Pan (god)|Pan]] | height_metric = | width_metric = | length_metric = | height_imperial = | width_imperial = | length_imperial = | diameter_metric = | diameter_imperial = | metric_unit = cm<!--don't leave blank—either don't include it, or include the default cm. --> | imperial_unit = in<!--don't leave blank—either don't include it, or include the default in. --> | dimensions = | dimensions_ref = | condition = | museum = | city = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States | coordinates = {{coord|40|48|29.6|N|73|57|45.2|W|region:US-NY_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | owner = | accession = | image_file = Columbia University, NYC (June 2014) - 27.JPG | material = [[Bronze sculpture|Bronze]] | url = <!--{{URL|example.com}} Only for official web pages--> }} '''''The Great God Pan''''' is an outdoor [[bronze sculpture]] of [[Pan (god)|Pan]] by American artist [[George Grey Barnard]] currently installed on the grounds of [[Columbia University]].
The work was originally commissioned by one of Barnard's most important patrons, [[Alfred Corning Clark]], for the interior courtyard of [[The Dakota]], an apartment building on [[Manhattan]]'s [[Upper West Side]]. However, it was never installed there. Upon completion, [[Alfred Corning Clark]] donated the sculpture instead to [[Central Park]]. After [[Alfred Corning Clark]]'s death, a permanent site for the sculpture could not be determined with [[Central Park]]. It was included in several exhibitions, including the [[Paris Exposition of 1900]], [[Pan-American Exposition]] in [[Buffalo, New York]] and the [[Louisiana Purchase Exposition]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QYhMAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA485&lpg=PA485&dq=pan+columbia+university+barnard+george+grey&source=bl&ots=I-SWGC_49v&sig=oyINFEXhK4YlBY6r-99whD5Z1cI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwimzJC0g_fSAhUPySYKHd-EBm44ChDoAQgeMAE#v=onepage&q=pan%20columbia%20university%20barnard%20george%20grey&f=false|title="The Great God Pan"|last=Carpenter|first=William H.|date=September 1908|work=Columbia University Quarterly|publisher=|year=|isbn=|volume=10|location=|pages=485-88|language=en}}</ref>
His son, [[Edward Severin Clark]], acting on behalf of his estate, ultimately donated the work to [[Columbia University]].<ref name=":0" /> [[Charles Follen McKim]] installed the sculpture as a functional fountain in the northeast corner of the campus in 1907. It is now located across from [[Lewisohn Hall]].<ref name="CUL">{{Cite web|url=http://library.columbia.edu/locations/avery/art-properties/public-outdoor-sculpture-at-columbia.html|title= Public Outdoor Sculpture at Columbia|accessdate=June 19, 2014|publisher=Columbia University Libraries}}</ref>
