[[File:Federal Court Canada.jpg|thumb|Winged sea caribou is used in the Coat of Arms of the Federal Court]] The '''Winged Sea Caribou''' is a [[mythical creature]] featured on the heraldic coat of arms of the [[Federal Court of Canada]] (FCC).
==History== In 2003, the Federal Court of Canada was recreated and separated from Federal Court of Appeal. This required the creation of a new coat of arms.<ref name = "lawyer weekly">{{cite magazine |last=Schmitz |first=Cristin |url=http://www.lawyersweekly.ca/index.php?section=article&articleid=896 |title=Federal Court chooses mythical creature for coat of arms |date=2009-04-10 |work=Lawyer's Weekly}}</ref> The original concept for the coat of arms was proposed by [[Robert Watt|Robert D. Watt]] and [[Claire Boudreau]] of the [[Canadian Heraldic Authority]].<ref name = "court" >{{cite web |url=http://cas-ncr-nter03.cas-satj.gc.ca/portal/page/portal/fc_cf_en/CoatofArms |title=The Federal Court's Coat of Arms |date=2013-01-04 |publisher=Federal Court}}</ref> It was painted by Eva Pilar-Cass and calligraphed by Doris Wionzek at a cost of $4,500.<ref name = "lawyer weekly" /> The coat of arms entered Public Register of Arms, Flags and Badges of Canada on December 10, 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://reg.gg.ca/heraldry/pub-reg/project.asp?lang=e&ProjectID=1203 |title=Register of Arms, Flags and Badges |publisher=The Governor General of Canada}}</ref> It was granted by [[Governor General of Canada|Governor General]] [[Michaëlle Jean]] in October 2008.
==Motto== The motto “Droit, Equity, Admiralty” means "law, equity and admiralty”.<ref name = "court" />
== Morphology == This fantastic Canadian beast has the head of a [[caribou]], the wings and claws of a [[raven]], and the posterior of a [[salmon]]. This unique morphology reflects the FCC's jurisdiction over federal land matters, aeronautics, and law of the oceans. The Federal Court of Canada website explains: "The winged sea caribou is a mythic creature representing the Court’s involvement with issues on the land, in the sea and other waters, and in the air. The three constituent creatures, the caribou, the raven and the salmon are found in many parts of Canada. The male and female supporters represent the equality of the sexes, as well as the fact that the Federal Court is {{sic|comprised |hide=y|of}} both male and female judicial officers."<ref name = "court" />
