{{BLP sources|date=March 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}} {{Infobox artist | name = Yael Bartana | Born = | image = Pressekonferenz zur Aktion „Zwei Minuten Stillstand“ von Yael Bartana-1482.jpg | image_size = 180px | caption = Yael Bartana, 2013 | birth_date = 1970 | birth_place = [[Kfar Yehezkel]], [[Israel]] | nationality = [[Israel]]i | field = [[Video art]] | training = [[Bezalel Academy of Arts and Design]] | movement = [[Israeli art]] | works = | patrons = | awards = | website = {{url|yaelbartana.com}} }}
'''Yael Bartana''' ({{lang-he|יעל ברתנא}}; born 1970, [[Kfar Yehezkel]], [[Israel]]) is an Israeli artist working in film, installation and photography. Her work investigates "the imagery of identity and the politics of memory."{{cn|date=June 2018}} She is perhaps best known for the film trilogy ''And Europe Will Be Stunned'', which premiered at the [[Venice Biennale#Poland|Polish pavilion]] of the 2011 [[Venice Biennale]] and explores notions of identity and nationalism inherent to the right of return.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Yael Bartana|journal=Modern Painters|date=2014|volume=26|issue=3|pages=27–29}}</ref> She is based in [[Amsterdam]], [[Berlin]], and [[Tel Aviv]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ago.net/meet-the-artist-yael-bartana|title=Meet The Artist, Yael Bartana|website=Ago|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref>
==Education== Bartana received a BFA in photography from the [[Bezalel Academy of Arts and Design]] Academy, [[Jerusalem]], a MFA in 1999 from the [[School of Visual Arts]], [[New York (state)|New York]], and was an artist in residence at the [[Rijksakademie|Rijksakademie van Beelden de Kunsten]] in Amsterdam for two years, ending in 2001.{{cn|date=June 2018}}
== Career == [[File:AND EUROPE WILL BE STUNNED.jpg|thumb|"...and Europe will be stunned", 2012 on the outside wall of Helena Rubinstein Pavilion for Contemporary Art]]Yael Bartana’s films, film installations and photographs challenge the national consciousness that is propagated by her native country of Israel. Bartana focuses her work on the implied meanings of terms related to "homeland", "return", and "belonging".{{cn|date=June 2018}} Her photography, film, and sound works investigate questions surrounding society, spirituality, and politics.{{cn|date=June 2018}}
Bartana's platform for investigation includes ceremonies, public rituals and social diversions that are intended to reaffirm the collective identity of countries. Working outside the country, she observes it from a critical distance. Her early films were primarily registrations in which aesthetic interventions, including soundtracks, slowing the image and specific camera perspectives, played a role.
Between 2006 and 2011, she was working in Poland, creating the trilogy ''And Europe Will Be Stunned'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EMG-Vk39m8M|title=Yael Bartana ...and Europe will be Stunned}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EMG-Vk39m8M|title=Yael Bartana ...and Europe will be Stunned|first=|last=SEA Foundation Tilburg|date=27 March 2012|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> which examines 19th- and 20th-century [[Europe]] as a historic homeland for [[Ashkenazi Jews]]. This is a project on the history of Polish-Jewish relations and its influence on the contemporary Polish identity. The trilogy represented Poland in the 54th International Art Exhibition in Venice (the [[Venice Biennale]], 2011). In recent years, she has increasingly staged her films, and proposed utopic narratives for new chapters of history.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/19/arts/design/yael-bartana-and-europe-will-be-stunned.html|title=Yael Bartana: And Europe Will Be Stunned|last=Smith|first=Roberta|date=18 April 2013|work=The New York Times|access-date=13 March 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> She was the first non-Polish citizen to represent Poland.
As a solo exhibition, her video trilogy has been on display at museums around the world.{{cn|date=June 2018}} In 2013 her film ''And Europe Will Be Stunned'' was acquired in the permanent collection by the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Foundation]] and the [[Tel Aviv Museum of Art]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.guggenheim.org/press-release/bartanaacquisition|title=Guggenheim and Tel Aviv Museum of Art Announce Acquisition of Yael Bartana Video|date=5 March 2013|work=Guggenheim|access-date=10 March 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>
Yael Bartana has had several solo exhibitions held at various venues including: the [[Museum of Modern Art, Warsaw|Museum of Modern Art]] in [[Warsaw]], [[Van Abbemuseum]] in [[Eindhoven]], [[MoMA PS1]] in [[New York City]], and [[Moderna Museet]] [[Malmö]]. She participated in [[Documenta]] 12 in [[Kassel]] in 2007, in the [[São Paulo Art Biennial]] 2010 and won the Artes Mundi Prize in 2010.<ref name="BBCNews">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/8692717.stm |title=Israeli Yael Bartana is Artes Mundi 4 winner |publisher=BBC.co.uk|date=19 May 2010 |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref>
== Awards and prizes == [[File:AND EUROPE WILL BE STUNNED2.JPG|thumb|AND EUROPE WILL BE STUNNED", 2012 on the outside wall of HELENA RUBINSTEIN PAVILION FOR CONTEMPORARY ART]]She has been nominated for and given many awards:{{cn|date=June 2018}} * 1996 Samuel Academy Award for Excellence, [[Bezalel Academy of Arts and Design]] Academy of Arts & Design, [[Jerusalem]] * 2003 Kipper Prize for the Young Artist, Wolf Fund * 2004 [[Dorothea von Stetten Art Award|Dorothea von Stetten Kunstpreis]] of the [[Kunstmuseum Bonn]]{{r|kb}} * 2005 Prix de Rome, 2nd Award Winner, Rijksakademie, Amsterdam * 2006 Prize for a Young Artist, Ministry of Science, Culture and Sport * 2007 Nathan Gottsdiner Foundation, The Israeli Art Prize, [[Tel Aviv Museum of Art]] * 2009 Prix Dazibao, Montreal (Canada) * 2010 [[Artes Mundi]] Prize, National Museum Cardiff (UK)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/8692717.stm|title=Israeli scoops Artes Mundi prize|date=19 May 2010|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> * 2010 Häagendaismo, Madrid (Spain) * 2010 Principal Prize by the International Jury and the Prize of the Ecumenical Jury at the Internationale Kurzfilmtage Oberhausen short film festival, Germany
==Exhibitions==
* Walker Art Center, [[Minneapolis, Minnesota]], USA (2013-2014)<ref>{{cite book|last=Vo|first=Edited by Bartholomew Ryan ; Texts by Yael Bartana, Liam Gillick, Renzo Martens, Bjarne Melgaard, Nástio Mosquito, Natascha Sadr Haghighian, Hito Steyerl, Danh|title=9 artists|year=2013|publisher=Walker Art Center|location=Minneapolis|isbn=1935963066|edition=First Edition.}}</ref> * Van Abbemuseum, [[Eindhoven|Eindhoven, The Netherlands]] (2012) * Art Gallery of Ontario, [[Toronto|Toronto, Canada]] (2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ago.net/yael-bartana-and-europe-will-be-stunned/ |title=Yael Bartana - ...And Europe Will Be Stunned |publisher=ago.net |date= |accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> * Media City Seoul 2010, [[Seoul]], Korea (2010) * Moderna Museet, [[Malmö|Malmö, Sweden]] (2010),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.modernamuseet.se/en/Malmo/Exhibitions/2010/Yael-Bartana/ |title=Yael Bartana - Moderna Museet |publisher=Modernamuseet.se |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> * Artes Mundi, [[Cardiff]], Wales (2010),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artesmundi.org/yael-bartana/ |title=Yael Bartana - Artes Mundi |publisher=Artesmundi.org |date=31 October 2009 |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> * Yael Bartana at P.S.1 (2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejewishmuseum.org/exhibitions/bartana09 |title=Special Exhibition - Mary Koszmary (Nightmares): A Film by Yael Bartana |publisher=The Jewish Museum |date= |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> * Foksal Gallery, [[Warsaw|Warsaw, Poland]] (2008) * Center for [[Contemporary art|Contemporary Art]], Tel Aviv, Israel (2008) * The Power Plant, [[Toronto|Toronto, Canada]] (2007) * Kunstverein Hamburg, [[Hamburg|Hamburg, Germany]] (2006) * Museum St. Gallen, [[St. Gallen]], Switzerland (2005) * MIT List Visual Arts Center, [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], USA (2004)
